AB  - During the past several decades, technological advancements in computer technology, enhancement in geographic information systems (GIS) software, availability of extensive environmental databases, and improvement in understanding of environmental processes, have significantly changed environmental management and natural resource planning. Resource managers and scientists are now using sophisticated spatial technologies, including GIS, simulation models, and geographically-referenced data to design effective and rational natural resource management programs. But, despite their many strengths the application of GIS in environmental management, for example, has been limited to static representation of dynamic space-time processes and the production of maps and reports. Although more advanced analytical functions for environmental modeling have been incorporated into most GIS software programs, the majority of these functions stand apart from the battery of methods in the management of environmental and natural resource systems. This paper examines the technical issues associated with the use of integrated spatial technologies for environmental and natural resource management. Two such spatial technologies are the major focus df this paper-GIS and simulation of environmental systems modeling. Case studies, involving the coupling of GLS with environmental models to form an integrated spatial decision support system for environmental management are presented. The progress made so far in integrating these two technologies are described and the challenging application issues and future research trends are identified.
