AB  - This study presents the development of JO-USAS, a locally modified Urban Sustainability Assessment System designed to address Jordan's specific urban challenges, including urbanization, resource constraints, environmental and socio-economic pressure from refugee surges. Integrating expert views, Structural Equation Modelling (SEM), and the Fuzzy Analytic Hierarchy Process (FAHP) offers a flexible, evidence-based instrument for ranking and evaluating urban sustainability indicators under uncertainty. An iterative process reduced 39 original indicators to 37, categorized in six main groups: Smart Location and Linkage, Sustainable Site Planning and Development, Natural Resource and Public Space Development, Sustainable Governance, Integrated Mobility Solutions, and Innovative Sustainable Development. Global weights analysis revealed high variation across categories, reflecting sensitivity to local priorities. Natural Resource and Public Space Development category recorded the highest (0.249), with emphasis on resource management and urgency of resilience, while Socio-Spatial Development recorded the lowest (0.052). Notably, indicators like Water Conservation (0.089), Energy Security (0.074), and Reduced Parking and Open Community recorded the highest weights, highlighting their critical contribution to Jordan's urban sustainability planning. FAHP effectively addressed subjectivity in expert judgment, enhancing system strength and real-world applicability. The flexible structure of the system and strong weighting process offer policymakers a decision-support tool responsive to Jordan's socio-environmental realities, with potential use in other resource-constrained settings. Future studies should involve testing JO-USAS on actual case studies to enhance its applicability, weighting accuracy, and stakeholder sensitivity, with ongoing relevance in changing urban environments.
