AB  - Computerised Decision Support Systems (DSS) are usually based on models that mimic biophysical and economic systems. DSS developers have assumed that accurate mimicry of physical and economic systems would serve to educate managers, leading to 'improved' thinking and better management. Few of these expectations have been met. So, this study examined factors that differentiate success from failure in the application of DSS, and the relevance of the DSS concept to the goals and strategies of decision makers. This study evaluates the relevance of 24 criteria of DSS design and application in six case studies. The most relevant criteria for impact of DSS related mainly to non-technical conditions (i.e. social, personal) affecting the usefulness of the DSS. Decision-making processes were also evaluated. While DSS in these case studies (and more generally) emphasise optimisation and simple, singular goals, the decision makers in the case studies often sought suboptimal solutions and had multiple goals. The DSS mostly aided choice between options, which is only one, albeit important, of several stages in a decision-making process. The current situation of general failure with agricultural DSS is partly explained by their narrow focus on technical issues and limited representation of decision-making processes. Holistic approaches to implementing DSS are required in order to avoid or surmount the non-technical barriers to the success of DSS. Management games provide settings that can help to successfully deliver some DSS and achieve outcomes such as increased flexibility, sustainability and profitability. Used in holistic settings, DSS can aid the transition of data and information into knowledge, from knowledge to better decisions and from situations of low sustainability and poor natural resource management to better situations.
