AB  - LIFECYCLE ASSESSMENT (LCA) IS INCREASingly used as a decision support tool by industry and government. The lifecycle impact assessment (LCIA) phase of the LCA tool has been standardized within the ISO 14000 family of standards and aims to quantify the environmental impacts of economic activities. The quantification process considers regional and global effects, rather than site-specific consequences as with environmental impact assessments. Various LCIA methods have been developed in Europe, which can be applied directly to provide a comparatively quick indication of the environmental influences of the industrial and economic systems evaluated. However, problems have been experienced with these methods in South Africa in terms of their comprehensiveness and modelling approaches. The scope therefore exists to develop a specific LCIA method for South Africa. This article proposes an LCIA framework and calculation procedure, based on available data from the environmental sciences. Decision-makers can use the procedure to obtain a measure of the environmental consequences of an economic activity on four natural-resource groups: air, water, land, and mined abiotic resources.
