TI  - Proposal to apply results of NASA-sponsored research for space operations to improve the quality and quantity of goods and services
T2  - SPACE OF SERVICE TO HUMANITY: PRESERVING EARTH AND IMPROVING LIFE
LA  - English
CP  - International Symposium on Space of Service to Humanity - Preserving Earth and Improving Life
AB  - NASA-sponsored research has produced a basic framework for characterizing space mission operations and for structuring systems that enable cost-effective operations planning and execution. The researchers never wavered from their focus on simplicity and generality as the means of realizing demonstrable operational effectiveness and life cycle economies. As a result, the framework can be transferred beyond the space program communities to domains that were not originally the targets of the effort.
   The story line of this paper is a proposal to transform the space operations results into innovative solutions for preserving Earth and improving life. The authors describe the space operations framework and suggest that its methodology, associated technology, and decision-support strategies can be applied in managing environmental factors, human capabilities, and natural resources that are the determinants of the quality of life on Earth. A concept for reusability of space mission program elements is also presented. Called ''Fundamental Reusables for Enterprise Deployment'' or ''FRED'', this was formulated in response to a challenge from the NASA Administrator to confront the status quo (of developing mission-peculiar, project-unique, and organization-specific systems) and recommend a target architecture for providing cross-cutting and cost-cutting Agency services for space mission operations. The authors propose to explore the relevance of a FRED-like concept for sustainable exploitation of a nation's resources. The paper is authored by members of NASA's COST LESS Team for Mission Operations, an international, interdisciplinary, and non-parochial team of government, industry, and academia, charged with reducing the cost of success for space mission operations.
