AB  - The management of natural resources in Protected Natural Areas needs to bring together the interests of many different stakeholders. For this purpose, multi-agent simulation systems (MAS) can be used to develop virtual environments in which the consequences of different management strategies on the ecosystem can be tested. In this context, a prototype of a MAS model was built for Sierra de Guara Natural Park (Spain, 80,739 ha), a typical Mediterranean mountain area where agricultural abandonment has occurred progressively in the last decades. In order to determine the evolution of vegetation types in time and space, information on current distribution of vegetation cover was used to set up the initial state of the model, which could change due to a 'densification' function defined from previous studies and that was dependent on management. According to the theory of states and transitions in vegetation dynamics, once a threshold was reached, a particular vegetation unit could change to a denser vegetation type. Three different management scenarios were evaluated: abandonment of agriculture and livestock production, with occurrence or absence of natural fires, and continuity of current farming practices (on 53% of the total Park area). Simulations were carried out until an equilibrium state was reached (60 to 80 years depending on scenarios). Agricultural abandonment led to a rapid densification of vegetation, with lower diversity at the equilibrium situation (higher proportion of forest cover). This trend was more irregular when natural fire was included in the model, and more grassland and shrub pastures were observed at equilibrium. Current farming practices still led to some changes in vegetation, but were mostly concentrated in non-used areas; vegetation cover diversity at equilibrium was higher in this scenario. The utility of this approach as a decision support tool, even at its preliminary stage, was demonstrated.
