FX  - The concept underlying CoLa Decision Support System (DSS) originated in a series of three grants from the Robertson Foundation to DWM (2012-2024) , focusing on Felid Landscapes with the paradigms of clouded leopards in Southeast Asia, lions in Africa and jaguars in South America. At the time the DSS was called the WildCRU Decision Support Toolkit (DST) . PJ, SJG, SC, ZK, and IG acknowledge support of the NASA Biodiversity and Ecological Conservation Applied Sciences program (grant #80NSSC21K1942) which supported integration and enhanced functionality of CDPOP and UNICOR into CoLa and development of the DSS. Additional funding for the underpinning fieldwork came to DWM from the Recanati-Kaplan Foundation and latterly Panthera. Dedicated field teams supported the camera-trapping work, and are gratefully acknowledged in the primary papers (many cited herein) . We are deeply grateful to the many people who have travelled with us on this journey, and especially to the national and international participants in our first generation of workshops between 2018 and 2022 in Sabah, Laos, Bhutan, Myanmar, and Zimbabwe and Botswana, all of whom played inspirational roles in shaping the final CoLa DSS. We are grateful for comments on this manuscript by Dr E.A. Macdonald. This research was supported in part by the USDA Forest Service, Rocky Mountain Research Station. The findings and conclusions in this publication are those of the authors and should not be construed to represent any official NASA, USDA, or U.S. Government determination or policy.
