AB  - A WWW-based Spatial Decision Support System (SDSS) has been developed which can be used to quantify the economic and water quality impacts of nutrient, pesticide and sediment management strategies at the field, watershed and basin level. The SDSS is modular in design and relies on GIS (geographic information systems) to link the economic, water quality and hydrologic models. The SDSS is most applicable for Midwestern US watersheds of varying size. Application of the SDSS provides farmers, local soil and water conservation district personnel, resource managers and policy decision-makers with information on the least cost means of improving water quality by reducing agricultural sediment, nutrients, and pesticides. The development approach that was utilized and the application of the decision support system are described. The various spatial modules, water quality models, databases, and Java (Internet) applets are available at the URL http://danpatch.ecn.purdue.edu/similar to sdss/.
