AB  - This study proposes a hybrid fuzzy decision-support framework for assessing the durability of soil and water conservation structures using UAV-acquired imagery. To address the inherent uncertainty and variability in visual inspections, a fuzzy inference classification mechanism was developed to analyze degradation patterns captured in aerial images. By applying fuzzy set theory and expert-informed semantic rules, the system translates ambiguous visual observations into standardized condition indices, enabling robust classification of structural deterioration. The resulting condition indices scores are integrated into an Analytic Network Process model, which prioritizes maintenance factors through weighted multi-criteria reasoning. This dual-layer architecture enhances semantic interpretability and rating consistency while supporting automated, large-scale infrastructure monitoring. Case results show that the fuzzy classifier significantly reduces inter-rater variation and improves classification reliability, particularly in borderline or degraded imagery scenarios. The proposed method provides a scalable, image-driven approach for infrastructure condition analysis and illustrates how fuzzy logic techniques can improve pattern recognition and decision support in real-world inspection applications.
