AB  - For many farmers, the task of assessing new methods and developing a plan for change is difficult, given that current methods are entrenched from years of experience and new methods are not well understood. The Planting and Residue Management System (FARMS) is a decision support system (DSS) developed to facilitate farmer testing of new conservation systems before testing and using them in the field. The computer-based DSS allows farmers to test alternative production systems under their specific farm conditions. FARMS was developed for western Canadian agriculture and applies the knowledge of crop residue management and performance of planting equipment for conservation systems to specific farm situations. An overview of the design of the system, the knowledge acquisition method and an example are provided. The system was developed in C++, rather than an expert system shell, because the complexity of the problem required more flexibility than shells allowed. The logic, data, and presentation within FARMS have been tested by researchers, extensionists and innovative farmers.
