AB  - The structural safety of traditional Chinese wooden architecture is crucial for cultural heritage conservation. Owing to the complex material variability, their long-term performance under natural hazards remains uncertain, calling for reliable assessment methods to support preventive conservation and risk-informed management. This study introduces a chain-like minimum-cutset Bayesian Network (BN) framework for the safety evaluation of traditional wooden structures. By integrating structural mechanics with probabilistic reasoning, the model enables both forward prediction of system failure probability and backward diagnosis of the most vulnerable components. A case study on a typical Chuandou-type wooden frame illustrates the applicability of the approach, demonstrating its capacity to identify critical joints and columns as dominant contributors to collapse scenarios. Compared to the conventional probability network estimation technology (PNET), the proposed method yields more consistent results and enhances the interpretability of failure paths. The findings provide heritage professionals with a decision-support tool that bridges engineering reliability analysis and conservation practice. By pinpointing weak members and quantifying their influence on global safety, the method supports the prioritization of monitoring, targeted interventions, and resource allocation. This contributes to the broader aim of preventive conservation by enabling timely and minimal intervention strategies for safeguarding traditional wooden heritage structures.
