AB  - Synergistic conservation of ecosystem services (ESs) and biodiversity is an important scientific basis for the construction of ecological conservation priority areas (CPA) and the formulation of conservation policies. However, the existing nature reserve system (NRS) mostly focuses on a single conservation objective, and there is a significant gap in the synergistic optimization of multiple ecological functions. This study takes Gansu Province, a key area of the ecological security barrier in northwest China, as the study area, and constructs a framework for identifying CPA in view of its high geographic heterogeneity and outstanding ecosystem vulnerability. Using multiple ES models, the spatial differentiation patterns of various ESs were estimated. Next, the Biomod2 integrated model was used to simulate the habitat suitability of the species, the representativeness-vulnerability framework was used to identify CPA with single and integrated targets, and the conservation efficiency and conservation gaps of CPA in Gansu Province NRS were assessed. The results indicate that the existing NRS provides less coverage of CPA in the combined perspective than in the single perspective. The area of conservation gaps in the CPA under the integrated perspective is lower than the area of conservation gaps under the single perspective, but still falls short of the conservation objectives of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF). In order to minimize the conflict between ecological conservation and social development, the spatial conflict between conservation and development needs to be mitigated through mechanisms such as cross-regional ecological compensation, the promotion of green agricultural technology, and the optimization of protected area networks. This study provides reference and decision support for the formulation of integrated multi-objective ecological protection policies.
